    <text id="R13258117T">
        <front id="d2">
            <div1 type="summary" id="d3">
                <p>Union General John Sedgwick reports to General In Chief Henry Halleck on January,
                    1864, troop movements. Sedgwick reports that Confederate General Henry Heth's
                    division had been in Staunton for Christmas.</p>
            </div1>
        </front>
        <body id="d4">
            <div1 type="letter" id="d5">
                <head>
                    HDQRS. ARMY OF THE POTOMAC,
                    <name type="recipient">Maj.-Gen. HALLECK,<lb/> Gen.-in-Chief:</name>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <date value="1864-01-17">January 17, 1864. (Received 3.30 p. m.)</date>
                    </dateline>
                    <salute/>
                </opener>
                <p>Your telegram to Gen. Meade has just been received. Gen. Meade has not returned.
                    Scouts from these headquarters returned this morning. Report Longstreet has had
                    no re-enforcements from Lee of late, and that Heth's division that went to
                    Staunton on Christmas is returning to its old camps. A deserter from the First
                    Maryland Cavalry (rebel), who left his regiment on the 13th instant, states no
                    re-enforcements have been sent away from Lee's army to Longstreet of late, and
                    everything is quiet.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute/>
                    <signed>JOHN SEDGWICK,<lb/> Maj.-Gen., Cmdg.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div1>
        </body>
    </text>
